Nestled within the usually-quiet @Milleniawalk, @bistrog.sg draws our attention with its botanical theme and visually-pleasing interior. 

We started off with the raved Lobster Bisque followed by the Australian Lamb Rack and Duck Confit Pasta. Honest take: Considering the price, we expected better in terms of the food portion and quality. But at these challenging times for F&B business, we could well understand the competitive pricings and quantities. 

Heading back for a second trip? No. Heading back on the account that the place is spacious with seating arragements safely arranged (especially important when you are masked off while eating and everyone is catching the +ve trend)? A Yes!  Head on down if you're nearby for some drinks or maybe other dishes we hadn't tried?

"What tea is on the menu?" This is probably the idea we brought along when we visit a TWG chain in Singapore, preparing ourselves to indulge in their quality and popular tea varieties with some tea time desserts to go along. And so we are proven wrong with the all-day mains featuring pastas to many kinds of western cuisines. 

While the V-day special menu featured on most of our plates (photos for reference and we did not do a full review anyway since they are off the menu at this juncture), the regularly featured wagyu tenderloin is one dish that captivates us from all angles. 

From the flavourful bearnaise sauce to the tenderness of the wagyu slices, accompanied by a matcha truffle drizzled fries, this dish is worth every feature in the atmospheric tea garden at MBS.

Relocating from the HDB-populated AMK neighbourhood estate to the cafe-populated Jalan Besar area, Obsessive Chocolat Desire (OCD) Ice Cream Cafe continues to serve wide range of wallet-friendly ice cream flavours. 

The signature chocolate ice cream stands out with different variations of chocolate to choose from based on origin and % of cacao. We had the gelato-like Africa 85% dark which is stickier and more robust in taste. 

With fierce competition within the vicinity, it will not be long to see more interesting additions by the cafe to spice up the menu further. Not a bad dessert place to hit after your Swee Choon and Curry Rice satisfaction.

As we are mentally prepared to join the snaking queues of KBBQ chains along the popular go-to Tanjong Pagar Street on a New Year Eve, our attention instantly switched towards a similar concept store with the name 'On Dol'. 

The plethora of vegetable choices to use as wraps was a pleasant surprise to us and we firmly believed that this is a one of a kind here in SG. Yes we admit we cant even call out half of the vegetable names but we are totally spoilt for choices with the wide range of banchan (side dishes including those to be grilled along the meat) and main dishes (besides meat; steamed egg, seafood stew) to come along. 

Not forgetting the highlight of the show with different cuts of pork meat which are grilled on hot stone by the friendly hyungnim. For $80++, you end your 2pax set meal with a choice of a hot stone pot rice or fried rice. We had the fried rice and the friendly staff reappeared to fry the fragrant rice with the remaining pork from the BBQ. There you have a tasty portion of fried Bibimbap. Look what the staff prepared for us!

„ÄéWhat we have tried„Äè
~ Set 2pax (included steam egg)
 Meat:
 - Grilled pork belly
 - Pork Jowl
 - Shoulder butt
 - Grilled thin-sliced pork belly

 - Pork and kimchi stew
 - Seafood soybean paste stew
 - Seafood and soft bean stew ‚úÖ

Choice rice (choose 1)
- Hot stone pot rice
- Fried rice ‚úÖ

If you enjoy thin-crust pizzas with a light slightly-chewy crust and crisp exterior, I would recommend you to give a try on this. @pizzaexpresssg , they offer every conceivable flavour eg:  vegan, spicy, tomato-based, and exquisitely-flavoured pizzas. Not only do they focus on pizzas, they do offer salads, pasta, desserts, teas, coffee, and alcoholic beverages as well!

‚≠êÔ∏èCarbonara Pizza
The crispy thin crust along with the b√©chamel and smoky crispy bacon. Love how the pizza was topped with a generous amount of mozzarella, parmesan and garlic oil on creamy b√©chamel base with a soft-cooked egg in the middle. One of the best things about this pizza is thin with chewy texture. This made quite a decent eat.
‚≠êÔ∏èLa Reine
A simple pizza and the dough was soft and tasty , they‚Äôre so generous with their ingredients eg. Mushrooms, olives, ham, mozzarella and passata. 

‚≠êÔ∏èSpicy Lemon Chicken Linguine
Spiced chicken slices with lemon, garlic and zucchini. Topped with fresh parsley and chilli flakes.
The linguine was topped with Spiced chicken slices with lemon, garlic and zucchini. It was spicy and inner juiciness.  It‚Äôs truly the best combination for a light and fresh spring dish that compliments the temps as they start to warm up!
We would definitely come back here again for more!üòâ

üìçPizzaExpress Holland Village

Satisfy your sweet tooth @madlygood_official . They do offer a variety of coffee and desserts. You can have an afternoon tea snack after shopping at Jcube. 

‚≠êÔ∏è The Original Buttermilk Waffles
Tried Original Buttermilk Waffles, the presentation and plating are loaded with strawberries and blueberries, lightly dusted with powdered sugar and lotus biscoff crumbs. Topped with Oreo wafer and butter biscuit for extra crunch. Overall, the waffles tasted really great and ice cream was smooth which paired well with waffles.

‚≠êÔ∏èMaple Staple Pancakes
Nothing can go wrong with Pancakes which has always been a breakfast staple. It was topped with granola, fresh strawberries, and strawberry sauce. Served with unsalted butter and maple syrup at the side. Such a delicious and satisfying meal.

This will be my final post for the year and will prolly not be able to post another one for an extremely long time, cos this post means the most to me; so much that tears are flooding my vision but I still need to dedicate this special post to a man that I've never ever cried so much for in my whole life - my boss. 

This guy is unlike any other boss - he's like a great mixture of a fatherly-like figure and at the same time that reliable older brother. He's someone I can comfortably cry to pretty much everyday for the whole day and he'd still stick by me (he prolly had no choice). THO. Sometimes he sucks at comforting me & makes me feel worse, ending up crying even more, making him feel like he should just slap himself lel.

I will miss his menopause moments where he gets angry outta blue & scold the shit outta me (till I cry again, DAMN IT MEL, WHY ARE YOUR TEAR GLANDS NOT DRY LIKE THE SAHARA DESERT BY NOW), and his cannot-make-it memory where he assumes he tells me things telepathically & scolds me thereafter AGAIN (LIKE NANI, BRUH). Jokes aside, I will miss defo his deep dimples, curly eyelashes, cute smiley and most of all, his comforting hug. I've been so lucky in my this life to have met a precious person like him, and more importantly work together with him as my boss. 

He EARNED my respect - something that OLDIES nowadays can't seem to get it from their irritating ancestral thinking. Yes, he scolds me alot but he also jokes alot with me. He teaches and encourages me. All in all, he's just really the best boss I've ever met (tho he is really useless at times lel no offence), and never in my life would I pledge my loyalty to anyone (since I'm a judemental bitch) but he deserve it. 

I will miss picking up your calls in Singapore and hearing your voice, but we shall meet again in South Korea once things are more settled. You will forever be etched in my memory - never to be forgotten and forever loved. Thank you, for everything. I have kept my promise to never leave your side till you go back to your home country, so I hope you're happy.

There's even more to say but I wish you all the best, especially till we meet again.

OK here's more, and with reviews!

First one is the 'Ramen House': Not bad. With the price and quality & quality is pretty good but defo not spicy enough for me. ALL their "spicy" dishes. And if their food is salty to me, yal best better be prepared to be bald when yal go home lel.

2ndly is the 'Ah Ma Bak Chor Mee' which is not bad but again not spicy nor salty enough for me. But your above-average BCM for sure.

3rd: 'Mr Holmes Bakehouse' or smth and service was pretty decent! Which made me wanna go back again cos their $7.90 +/- tiny Jalape√±o Ranch Bacon Danish is defo not enough to bring me there again.

Last but not least, 'Soi Thai' I think. Food was wayyyyy below average to a point that the Mama Instant Noodles that yal cook yourself would be better. BUT. They were open to constructive feedback and actually waived off one of the most expensive dishes on the bill, so I'm willing to go back and try one of the days.

Ok folks! Have to be honest, when it come to food, nothing beats a simple comforting plate of Hokkien Mee! It‚Äôs fragrant prawn broth, it‚Äôs strand of noodles mix with bee hoon, It‚Äôs chili and not forgetting it‚Äôs price point!

So I‚Äôm so glad to share that @namsinghokkienfried who are the masters of these dish are expanding, and their newest outlet is at their 1st ever West-side stall at Blk 177 Bukit Batok West Ave 8, Get Together Coffee Shop.
üîª
Not to worry folks, Nam Sing Hokkien Fried Mee still uses the same techniques created by the first generation, following a very specific recipe set by Ng Tong and Ng Seng. Firstly, instead of using yellow noodles and thick bee hoon, Nam Sing uses thin bee hoon from the same supplier they used from the 1940s. The noodles easily absorb the bold flavours of the prawn and meat broth the noodles are stir-fried in, while lending the entire dish a subtle wok hei fragrance without masking the broth flavours.
üîª
These are indeed evident as we slurp these in record timing! Very thankful that these hawkers stick true to their passion without compromising on its tradition! It‚Äôs only with 2nd generation hawkers from Nam Sing Hokkien Fried Mee, that helps to keep our hawker food alive and to carry our local flavors and food all the way beyond the 21st century!!

Known simply as ‚ÄòGurney Drive‚Äô, the restaurant is named after and inspired by the Gurney Drive in Penang (Malaysia). The street was famous in the early 1970s and 1980s for its delicious ‚Äòhawker food‚Äô sold from food stalls along the seafront. Having closed all their outlets in Singapore in 2015 due to the departure of their then-Penangite chef, fans will be delighted that the well-loved brand has now made a comeback after seven years in a place befitting the food it serves. Nestled within Northshore Plaza II, Singapore‚Äôs first seafront neighbourhood centre built within an HDB estate, one can now enjoy yummy Penang hawker signatures along the seafront!

From Penang Fried Kway Teow, Assam Laksa to Prawn Noodles, Gurney Drive offers the same staggering variety of Penang hawker food, all served with a generous topping of their crowd-favourite fresh crisp-fried pork lard.

description:
#GohEatSpain #7of10üçØ #ShouldGoh to Antig√ºedades Bar de Tapas in Seville, just a stones throw away from the Seville Cathedral for tapas.

The place was packed for dinner and we managed to grab a table for dinner. 

Had the Garlic Prawns, which came bubbling which was terrific with bread.

The Fried Aubergine with Salmorego and Molasses was crisp with a tender centre -‚Äòs nice sweetness from the molasses.

The Pork with Cheese Sauce was tasty but a little tough.

The Chicken with Orange Sauce was interesting, with a creamy sweet orange sauce, but the chicken breast was way overcooked and dry.

I also got to try Vino de Naranja or Seville Orange Wine, where they take A sweet white wine in nearby Huelva and age it with the peel of some Seville bitter orange. The wine was really sweet with a strong orange perfume, and it was really strong too.

#GohEatSpain #7of10üçØ #ShouldGoh to @confiterialacampana to try out their bakes and the lenten treat of Torrijas. 

They are said to make some of the best in Seville but only make them close to the period of lent, as the highly sugary and calorific properties are supposed to make up for those abstaining from meat.

La Campana have been following the same recipe for over a century. Their bread is homemade on-site and soaked first in a brine made with water, wine and salt. After frying the slices, they get soaked again in a syrup made with honey and sugar.

It was highly sweet and perhaps would go perfectly with an espresso.

#GohEatSpain #8of10üçØ #ShouldGoh to @barelcomercio for their Churros and Chocolate.

Founded in 1904, this long-standing bar serves up tapas but are really well known for their churros, so much so that there‚Äôs a dedicated churros station by the bar. The churro were really light and crisp and fried in a huge coil and cut to order. These reminded me of you tiao back home as they weren‚Äôt dusted with sugar like I‚Äôm used to. Was still really delicious dipped in the thick hot chocolate. 

Maybe I should start dipping my you tiao in milo back home. ü§£

#GohEatSpain #8of10üçØ #ShouldGoh to @casamoralessevilla a local Seville institution since 1850.

A really interesting space with huge earthenware wine jugs lining the walls. The food was pretty good too!

We started out with a Pringa sandwich, mix of braised meat and sausages in crusty bread, delicious.

Next was their Pork Meatballs, I‚Äôm not really sure what was in the sauce but it was really tasty, and I mopped it all up with the accompanying bread.

We also had Pulpo - Octopus which was simply done, on top of boiled potatoes and a dusting of paprika. It was really tender.

Lastly, we had a house classic, Chicken and Mushrooms in Sherry, you could taste the sweetness the sherry imparted in the dish.

#GohEatSpain #5of10üçØ #CanGoh to @freiduriapuertadelacarne for some Pescaito Frito.

Was in town during the Sevilla FC v West Ham United Europa League Round of 16 1st Leg Match, so decided to soak in the atmosphere and watch the match on tv in our apartment (the cheers echoed in the streets when Sevilla scored the 1 and only goal of the match), took a stroll during half time to get some mixed fried fish and got back in time to watch the 2nd half and the goal.

The was a mix of hake, sardines, cod bites, prawns and cuttlefish. The fish wasn‚Äôt that crisp as it may have sat out for awhile before I ordered and seasoning was abit varied with some pieces being overly salty. Think it would be much better if you get there as it comes straight out of the fryer.

WaWa have made us go ohh Lala ~ Took us real long to try out their lala bee hoon and their signature cockles. The clams are so fresh, sweet and briny with a slight hint of seawater. They are so well treated and cleaned, no one ever likes it when the sand are not purged out from the clams clean. That you can be well assured there wouldn‚Äôt be any surprises as you dig in. The hearty broth boiled with lots of ginger slices and rice wine are the perfect food after a rain. 

And now onto the cockles, Wawa again have very much warmed the cockles of our hearts üòÇ It is stated on the menu board as a best seller and we do not dispute on that. It is so plump and juicy and the citrusy (house) sauce makes it more addictive, we can‚Äôt seem to stop eating it. 

This was pretty much Gobbler‚Äôs last few comfort meals just before he realized he got hit with Covid. He‚Äôs all well now and crying out to have this again. 

Featured here: 
- Signature Power Drunken Lala Beehoon
- Fresh Cockles Marinated in Wawa Special Sauce 
- Fresh Lala Chawamushi

Is not easy to find any good laksa at CBD area so this has been Nibbler‚Äôs go to laksa spot whenever she craves for it.

One of my favourite Singaporean dishes - wonton mee üòã Eat it anytime of the day: breakfast, lunch, dinner and even for supper!

Do you know that in Asia we sometimes drink our coffee with butter? It‚Äôs not only meant to give the coffee a richer flavour and added aroma, but in theory the fat in the butter slows digestion so that the caffeine in the coffee is slower to absorb to give you a longer-lasting kick! I had this delicious fluffy waffle at @ollacoffee which was topped with a scoop of Nanyang Kopi (coffee) guyou (butter) gelato and crushed butter crackers! It also came with a side of kaya. I loved it! Singaporean breakfast reimagined üòçüòã
The day my mother bought me both nasi lemak AND laksa for lunch and in the same breath asked me how come I‚Äôve gained weight üôÑ

Favourite dish: The grilled pork belly ü§§

One of our highlights this week was dining in at Cafe Football ‚öΩÔ∏è Located in PUB Recreation Centre, this restaurant has an awesome Football theme which captures the essence of football by bringing football fans and foodies together ü§© They have happy hour going on from Mon to Fri 4-7pm, with draught beers going at $10 per pint üòú üçª
.
It was tough choosing from their extensive East meets West menu as everything looked so good ü•∫ We finally decided on Crayfish Horfun and Fish and Chips for our mains.
.
The Crayfish Horfun was our personal favourite. A generous portion of silky hor fun was served with two halves of a crayfish, prawns and squid. The crayfish was succulent and juicy, and we really loved how the fresh seafood complemented the umami rich sauce. Definitely a must-try here!
.
Bring along a mate if you would like to try the Fish and Chips. Two huge fillet of battered snapper served alongside crispy truffle fries and a generous portion of salad is guaranteed to satisfy your hunger. It's quite rare to see fish and chips being served with fresh lettuce, so I would give this a big thumbs up üëç 
.
Le husband really loves the honey glazed chicken and he couldn't stop raving about it ü•≤ The chicken pieces were juicy and tender, coated in a glaze that was akin to those Korean chicken. There were some pieces of garlic cloves at the bottom which attests to the authenticity of the garlic soy sauce flavour.
.
We ended our meal with a sweet dessert. The waffles were served hot and crispy, drizzled with honey and chocolate sauce üòã
.
Thanks Irene at @cafefootballsg for the immaculate service and tour, we really loved our meal today and will definitely be back again with friends for happy hour ü§©ü§©
.

BRB drooling over this fine piece of work!!! Always passed by Lad & Dad and finally got the chance to try the crowd's favourite fish and chips and scotch eggs.
.
We couldn't resist trying the Scotch Egg ($12). The soft boiled egg was wrapped in a hearty pork sausage meat and covered in glorious golden bread crumbs sitting atop purple slaw.  As usual, this was gone within seconds despite taking small bites of it at a time ü•µ
.
We also shared a large serving of Fish and Chips ($28). The beer battered atlantic haddock fish indeed lived up to our expectations - the silky smooth flesh was firm yet flaky, encased within a golden crispy light batter. For the sides, we really love the crispy thick cut chips that were seasoned well üòã Drizzled Heinz malted vinegar over the dish which had the right amount of acidity cutting gently through the crispy, fried texture.
.

Flutes Restaurant indeed lives up to their name of being an award-winning fine dining European restaurant. We tried out their Valentine's Day menu ($98+) and really loved the prompt service and lovely ambience.
.
Ranking the food in order of flavours, our favourite dish has got to be the Barbequed Wanderer Barley Fed Beef Striploin. We opted for medium rare, and was treated with a super juicy and tender meat. Served together with Jerusalem artichoke and asparagus, I found it interesting that they used hazelnut and sauce perigord which added an extra nutty dimension to the overall flavour profile ü§§
.
The Pan-fried Foie Gras was an absolute gastronomic delight!!! It was served warmed, topped with caramelised Sarawak pineapple, chocolate and coriander. The pairing might seem strange, but the rich umami flavour totally blew us away :") So glad that we opted to top up $22 for this.
.
We were pretty impressed with the Carpaccio of Robbins Island Wagyu. It looks stunning on the plate with thinly sliced wagyu beef garnished with huitlacoche mustard, black truffle and grissini. The buttery texture was just *chefs kiss* ü§§
.
Have always been curious about the foam technique used in Top Chef, and we finally tried shellfish foam that complemented the Roasted Skull Island Prawn. The lobster oil added a fragrant touch that made us wolf this down within seconds.
.
Another lovely dish was the Snapper Fillet. The truffled chicken essence, with its totally complex flavours, nicely enhanced the flavour of the fried sweet snapper flesh.
.
It was our first time trying Paris-Brest, which consisted of crispy choux pastry and a praline flavoured cream with Kirsch Cherry. Being a decadent sweet dessert, it definitely appealed to my sweet tooth ü•µ
.
Unfortunarely, there was nothing much to shout about for the South Australian Lobster ‚ÄòLasksa Noodles‚Äô. The portion was quite small for a top up at 22+ ü•≤
.

The Brewing Ground has been on my cafe list since forever, and we finally travelled down to Joo Chiat to give it a try. Located within an old school compound, we absolutely love the chill vibes here and their decor is just üíØ! Although the prices were on the higher side, the portions were huge and their coffee was pretty decent as well.
.
The Crab & Signature Scrambled Eggs On Toast ($25) looked really appetising with saut√©ed crabmeat and ikura sitting atop a slice of sourdough. Sad to say, I wasn't a huge fan of the taste as it tasted rather acidic and funky for my liking ü§£ 
.
The Breakfast Burger ($20) fared a little better in my opinion, which was a "zenged up" version of Macs sausage egg mcmuffin. The pork sausage patty complemented the silky scrambled eggs and caramelized onions. Also loved the brioche buns which were grilled perfectlyüòã
.
We were also intrigued by the Cod Fish & Chips ($20) which had a crispy batter and firm flesh encased within. Would have preferred the meat to be more buttery and flaky.
.

Wowzers this weekend has been fulfilling!! Stumbled upon a hidden gem at Sen of Japan, and we were pretty impressed with the quality of the food. Furthermore, we also used Burpple Beyond for their mains which made it all the more worthwhile. The portions might seem small but we really savoured every bite and it was a good meal with a hot sake to pair dem dishes with ü§§
.
The Black Cod Soy is a velvety and flaky soy-glazed black cod fillet that's marinated well with Hiro‚Äôs special soy marinade. The glaze tasted distinctively of soy sauce and something sweet like honey(?) which combined smoothly with the rich, savory soy sauce. 
 .
The Uni Pasta was our second favourite ü•∫ So very creamy and fresh, the uni had a subtle yet pleasant sweetness to it. The pasta was also topped with sakura ebi, ikura and truffle mushroom cream sauce that made each bite fragrant and simply stunning!! Just wish that there was more uni to pair the pasta with ü•µ
.
We were also won over by their Anago Tempura ($20) which is saltwater eel tempura that had a light and crisp batter encasing sweet and delicate eel meat.
.
Last but not least, we didn't forget our greens! Got the Inaniwa Salad ($19) which is a mixed salad with chilled inaniwa udon noodle, crab meat, prawns and golden miso dressing. Love the sweet umami combination of this.
.

Had a great time explored to @timbreplus.eastside  @ Expo, which is a green and sustainable food park. It offers a diversity of restaurant-grade food and casual eats at affordable prices. 

‚ô¶Ô∏è @streetsofbangkok.sg 
üåüTom Yum Mama Hotpot ($12 for 1 person)
Mama noodles in tom yum broth with topped with prawns, fish slices, mussels, squid, mushrooms, meatball and eggs. The  tom yum broth was so appetising! The sourness and spiciness were on point! There were huge amount of lemongrasses which made it refreshing as well! I have been transported to Thailand üáπüá≠ when i was having this dish ü§≠ The noodles which soaked in the tom yum soup was so flavourful üòã It‚Äôs value of money as they are generous with the amount of seafood givenüëçüèª

üåüMoo Ping - Thai grilled pork skewers ($5.5/ 3 pieces)
The pork skewers were perfectly gilled and it‚Äôs well marinated! The pork was sooooo tender and taste of the pork was on the sweeter side. Love it ‚ù§Ô∏è

‚ô¶Ô∏è @ajiyasg 
üåüOkonomiyaki $17
You can mix and match 3 ingredients out of the seafood, meat and veggies categories. I have chosen prawns, scallop and kimchi. The okonomiyaki was packed with the chosen increments and also other ingredients such as cabbage and onions. It‚Äôs tasted great to be eaten with the  mayonnaise, okonomiyaki sweet sauce and huge amount of bonito flakes on top! However, I would prefer if the okonomiyaki to be crispier on the edge. Highly recommended to consume it when it‚Äôs warm. It‚Äôs a decent one but definitely not the best. üòÜ

This timber+east side  is a great concept and I will be back to try out other stalls such as the stalls selling pizza, sawarak delicacy etc!

This week I will be embarking on a mini series featuring an array of seafood. First off, the barramundi. I am no self-proclaimed expert when it comes to fish but I would probably say that besides salmon, barra is the fish I probably have cooked the most of, owing to my time in Australia. 

Subtle in flavour, this fish works well with many different sauces. I am pairing mine with a sauce made from the juice extracted while steaming clams and coconut milk. Using aromatics like ginger, lemongrass and kaffir lime helps add to the fragrance of the sauce. The asian herb salad also helps provide freshness to the dish 

Today I will be sharing a loose recipe focusing on the clam and coconut sauce while I found absolutely delicious! You might want to try this out for yourself

1. Add sliced garlic, shallots and olive oil to a pan
2. Add your clams and stir for about 30s
3. Add white wine and cover with a lid
4. Once the clams open, strain out the liquid and pick the clam meat
5. Simmer the clam juice with lemongrass, ginger and kaffir lime leaves and top up water if needed 
6. Add coconut milk and adjust seasoning to taste with salt or fish sauce

[Fuku Don] - Invited Tasting
Do you love Japanese don? Here's some affordable options in Punggol to check out! üòâ

Wagyu Onigiri Don ($15.90)
Soft and tender wagyu beef slices here! Really enjoyed the texture, and it's properly seasoned! I wouldn't mind some sauce for the rice tho ü§≠.

Chicken Oyakodon ($5.90)
Honestly really affordable for the huge portion here! Chicken breast is used for the Katsu, so it's slightly drier, but it's still soft in terms of texture! Katsu aside, the don is pretty flavourful overall, and I liked that the egg was also pretty soft & goes well w/ the sauce! 

Asian Garlic Pur√©e Salmon Onigiri Don ($7.90)
Their homemade Asian Garlic Puree used for the Salmon is not a flavour that you'd usually find anywhere else. Altho not my personal favourite, but it's a pretty unique one nonetheless!

Sides:
Crunchy Chili Chicken Karaage ($4.90)
Q an interesting side dish, and it's really worth it for the price! Each piece of chicken was soft and tender, and was lightly crisp on the outside as well. Only qualm was the sauce was slightly salty!

Homemade Potato Salad ($2.50)
For those who love potato salad, this is a pretty hearty one to go w/ your meals!

Definitely a place with good potential, and with such affordable pricing I wouldn't mind coming back if I'm near the area ü§≠.

Thank you @dtfoodaffair for inviting and @fukudonsg for hosting!

[Kulto]
Another once-a-month Spanish food gathering, and this time to try @kulto.sg!

Octopus 'Galician Style' ($32)
The texture here was good! Q soft and tender, and the sauce is not bad, just that I personally prefer those that comes with a smokey or burnt flavour.

üåü Iberico Chorizo, Confit potato & Soft Eggs ($24) üì∏ 3
The chorizo was slightly smokey, and had a good bite, which also went well with the potato and runny eggs ü§§. The addition of onions was also üíØ! Oh how much I'd love to have this for breakfast regularly üòç.

Jamon Iberico Croquettes & Crab Croquettes ($14/ 4 pcs) üì∏ 4, 5
They usually sell in 4 pcs, but you can choose to get 2 of each flavour instead. Jamon Iberico tasted like carbonara in a croquette, but can't put my finger on which shop's carbonara it's similar to. For the Crab Croquette, it was really similar to the sauce used in dry laksa pasta.

üåü Homemade Cheese Terrine with Truffle & Honey Olive Oil ($22) üì∏ 6
Really creamy and light cheese that's similar to cream cheese texture. Very mild mushroom fragrance and flavour, I loved this combination! Super crispy bread to pair with too, defo enjoyable!

Charcoal Lamb Rack with Carrots & Caramelised Baby Onions ($38) üì∏ 7
The baby onions nicely helps to mask the gaminess of the lamb. The pairing sauce was slightly sour, reminding of vinegar. 

Seafood Paella (2-3 pax $39) üì∏ 2
This was literally the most hyped dish here but ended up being the most disappointing one here? The rice texture really no-go, it was pretty hard (not crispy), similar to undercooked rice. The juice from the prawn head also made it really fishy, which we didn't really enjoy. 

üåü Kulto Cheesecake ($14) üì∏ 8, 9
The cheesecake was really molten and quite creamy! The sorbet was really tangy - personally not a fan of the sorbet here, so would just go for the cheesecake. 

Whiskey Cake with Almonds ($14) üì∏ 10
Actually didn't expect them to pour whiskey over the cake, because we expected the whiskey to be infused instead. Whiskey is definitely strong and slightly spicy. Cream is really light, but reminiscent of the traditional bakery vanilla cream cake. Great for those who love whiskey!

Overall Rating: 8/10

[Milano Pizza & Wine] 
@milanopizzasg is a sister of @pastabar_sg, and I was really excited to finally book a seat to try it!

Sicilian Grandma Pizzas (6" square, 2" deep pie):
Let's first talk about the dough - their Grandma Pizzas use sourdough, so it's slightly tangy in flavour. I'd say it's really unique, with it being slightly thick, crispy on the outside and slightly airy on the inside! 

Mortadella & Burrata ($27++)
This was probably my favourite that night! We had 1-2 pizzas before this, so I really loved how the burrata helped to cut through some of the greasiness with its light and creamy flavour. The mortadella isn't strong unlike meats like Parma ham, so you don't get to taste much of the meat as a whole.

Truffle Mushroom ($38++)
This came with truffle cream and fresh shaved truffle, but you only get a slight hint of truffle. Expected it to be really strong, but the mixed mushrooms are instead more overpowering. Personally would prefer even stronger truffle flavour, but those who love mushroom flavours more would prefer this.

Neo-Neopolitan 12" Pizzas:
Beef Cheek Bolognese ($34++) üì∏ 4
Slow-simmered beef cheek. Felt that their neopolitan pizza doughs are slightly tougher, especially once it cools a little. 

Sausage & Hot Chilies ($28++) üì∏ 5
Homemade pork sausage is used here, and comes with pickled hot chillies. Didn't remember this to be spicy tho!

Korea town ($32++) üì∏ 6
You do taste Korean flavours, which comes from the Gochujang & kimchi. Overall decent pizza, except some slices of the Marinated Short Rib were really chewy and almost impossible to bite through (we were guessing tendon?).

Desserts:
Amalfi Lemon Meringue Pie ($16++)
This was good! The lemon was surprisingly not really tangy, and the pie was of the flaky kind with layers similar to millefeuille. Overall paired with the basil cream, this was q a delight to have.

Tiramisu Pie ($16++)
I tried this before the lemon meringue, and I really liked the tiramisu flavour! But this really took the backseat once I had the lemon meringue pie.
The pie here was quite dry and didn't have much flavour - wouldn't mind to remove the pie entirely, and just serve tiramisu üòÇ.

Overall Rating: 7/10

For 90 minutes, you get to enjoy buffet with free flow soft drinks! You also get to pick the sauce for your hotpot - we got Classic (Homemade + Gungjung) & Rose (Carbonara + Volcano).

[Don Lechon]
Have you tried Filipino food before? I've had decent ones previously, and this place was pretty famous for their pork, so I was really excited to head down to try it.

You can choose to get rice meals/ order dishes ala carte here, but the former will come with rice and smaller portion of meat that's more suitable for 1 pax.

Lechon Sisig Ala Carte ($14)
This was the better of the 2 dishes. It's meant to be piping hot when served, but it only sizzled for a good 15s before it stopped, which was pretty disappointing. The meat here was quite flavourful and went well with rice, but it's apparently meant to be crispier. (Swipe to 3rd üì∏ for sizzle)

Chopped Lechon (0.5kg - $22, 1kg - $40)
I came here for these, but these were served cold, which already meant what we were having weren't of the best quality. Some pieces of skin were crispy, but there were some that were very hard and almost impossible to bite through. There's nothing special about the pork here as well other than its thick cut.

Overall pretty disappointing, and after being hyped for such a long time, I guess the standards have really dropped drastically.

Overall Rating: 5/10

Was a bit skeptical before trying this place as I saw some bad reviews about the food. We went there with not too high expectation, ordered Omakase Sashimi, Kaiden Don and Fish Tacos. 
- Omakase Sashimi: it was ok for the price you‚Äôre paying for, fresh but definitely not as excellent as some other high end sushi places, you get what you pay for and this is a place with a really reasonable price for omakase sashimi
- Kaiden Don: we loved this dish, from the presentation to the taste. This is my bf‚Äôs favorite dish
- Fish Tacos: super crispy deep fried seaweed with amazing cuts. Can‚Äôt complain anything about this one

Kept in mind that the place will be really crowded in the weekend, we arrived there pretty early, maybe around 4pm, and after 10 mins you started to see people coming. We were first in line and got seated right after they opened. A tip is to know what you‚Äôll order beforehand since it might take a while for order to be prepared. They‚Äôre definitely understaffed. Our foods were served after 10-20 mins, which surprised me a lot after reading so many bad reviews about timing. 

Overall, a good place to try out and don‚Äôt forget to order hot sake for your meal!

In the beginning,
many looked down their noses

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs alot of hard work!‚Äù

Of our adamance to pursue
only what we‚Äôre inspired by,
how little clue they had.
Much less clue did they have
that with some imagination and
a surfeit of grit and elbow grease
and time, a manually onerous process
can metamorphose into one that‚Äôs
methodically simple and transferable
the better to stall a worthy tradition
from returning to dust
like the fate of many before it.

Checked out new Argentinian restaurant @bochinchesg for Xmas with my fav foodie friends ü•∞ company was 10/10, highly recommend, but food less so (unfortunately)
‚Äî
First, the empanadas. To be fair, I‚Äôve never had them before so I‚Äôm not sure if this is an issue of execution or just personal preferences but the pastry wasn‚Äôt crisp and was on the drier (and more crumbly) side. Fillings were okay. Very cheesy, which I enjoy, but the aromatics used didn‚Äôt come out as strongly as I‚Äôd like. That said, I‚Äôve always enjoyed stronger flavor profiles so that could just be me!
‚Äî
Quail was good. Wouldn‚Äôt say it‚Äôs particularly juicy, but it was well-seasoned and not too gamey. The accompanying potatoes had a really nice smokey flavor to it, but texturally, a bit gummy üò≠ taste-wise, a good combination though. Steak was also well-seasoned and had a nice sear. Not a stand-out but no complaints on it from me
‚Äî
As for desserts, they were pretty good! Doughnut balls could have been airier, but the flavours were all well balanced. Really enjoyed the yogurt-based tang in the Tres Leches. Also appreciated how they paired the chocolate fondant with avocado yuzu ice cream rather than vanilla- the latter would have been too sweet and rich! This was much more palatable imo
‚Äî
Edit: not sure why the fondant pic didn‚Äôt post but you can find it in my highlights 
‚Äî

description:
[SG] Desserts from @gaggan_anand 2.0 at @mandalaclub.sg! Will talk about the savoury dishes separately, but definitely enjoyed these over the yummy but slightly lacklustre tiramisu of version 1.0 üòÖ
‚Äî
Featured first is a marriage of Japanese strawberries, hay ice cream, caramel and mixed crumble- it was smokey, sweet and honestly, very summery ‚ú®. The strawberries were quite fresh and while they look sweet, they were actually a little tangy. Though I‚Äôm usually not a fan of sour tastes, in this case, I actually preferred it as it provided some much needed balance. In some ways, this dessert reminded me of @lebonfunk‚Äôs celery & buckwheat custard (which y‚Äôall know I love) in how the flavours interact with each other and taste completely different together than individually!! Personally, I‚Äôm always dazzled by how ingredients can have unique taste profiles depending on what they‚Äôre paired with~
‚Äî
Second dessert is the snowman cookie‚Ä¶ which yes, doesn‚Äôt really look like a snowman, but that‚Äôs because I captured it upside down oops üòÇ. Bit down on this deep fried beetroot cookie glazed with powdered sugar and was pleasantly surprised to find it filled with a cold sweet cream. Also a little tangy, also very refreshing, and generally appreciated following a carb-heavy main
‚Äî
Lunch: S$280++

[SG] desserts from @publico_sg! Not bad but a touch sweet for my liking. Tiramisu was interesting- definitely on the thinner side and not at all authentic, but the Kahlua flavor was very prominent, which I enjoyed ‚ò∫Ô∏è
‚Äî
Publico Tiramisu: S$15++
Chocolate Ecstasy: S$16++

We took advantage of a warm evening for dinner on the patio with good friends @lyonhall in Clarendon.  Of course we slipped up by not making a reservation, but they did a great job squeezing us in.  Like their website says, they really are a bustling brasserie.  #lunchatthebar #lyonhall

Always love visiting @smokecraftbbq in Clarendon, recently named one of the best barbecue joints in the D.C. area by @tim_carmen in @washingtonpost . They are also big on the competitive circuit taking 5th place in pork and finishing a very respectable 8th place overall at the 32nd Annual Jack Daniel's World Championship Invitational Barbecue in October 2021. #lunchatthebar #smokecraftbbq

Our recommendation when visiting @openroadgrill in Merrifield is to start with a Maple Old Fashioned and the gratis basket of popcorn. After that, the menu is strong with a wide assortment of salads, sandwiches, pizza, and entrees to sate your appetite. #lunchatthebar #openroadgrill

We have enjoyed Spanish Diner in @littlespain in NYC‚Äôs @hudsonyards so we were excited when @chefjoseandres decided to bring @spanishdiner to Bethesda, Maryland right here in the DMV. This location features plates from the Principality of Asturias, an autonomous community in northwest Spain. Spanish comfort food indeed! #lunchatthebar #spanishdiner

We are old enough to remember when @clareanddons was located in the 3000 block of Wilson Blvd. in Clarendon. They moved to more spacious digs in Falls Church around, we believe, January 2007. This is still our go to place for a fresh fish sandwich or a crab cake among other delights. Although it fashions itself as a beach shack, do not overlook its Mexican food which always hits the mark. #lunchatthebar #clareanddons

Fav pastry - TBB Green Tea Almond Croissant. Think flaky puff pastry, paired with rich green tea almond paste, topped with lavish roasted almond flakes, nutty almond goodness. P/S: munching the almond flakes drop from the croissant is actually the best part, every single flake countsüòÅ
‚Ä¢
TBB serves a good selections of Gryphon tea. My usual picks include this Chamomile Dream - pleasant hints of lemon verbena, lemongrass & lavender. Not the typical chamomile blend.
‚Ä¢
Sunday - have croissant, have tea, have fun!

San Mee(ÁîüÈ∫µÔºâ@ Ho Kee Seafood $5

üçú For my foreign friends, this dish is basically deep fried noodle with gravy. The ingredients usually include seafood like prawns and fish. Also pork too. 

The noodle they used is thin egg noodles and it has a chewiness when fried. I like that but some people might prefer a more crunchy San Mee.  I like that the ingredients are generous and lots of veggies! The gravy/broth is full of the umami of the seafood. This stall does produce quality zhi char(stir fried dishes) too.

üçΩÔ∏è Kway Chap Set@yukeeduck $4.50

üçú The set comes with a bowl of Kway Chap and a plate of fishcake, dried beancurd(Tao pok), pork belly, pork skin, pork intestine and one whole egg. 
The Kway Chap is not too thick and the broth is light not too herbal-ish. 

The pork belly is a bit tough and the skin and intestine is not properly cleaned as u can see hair on the skin and the intestine still has an odour but not too bad. The braise is on the sweeter side. But any foul smell can be masked with some vinegar chilli üòÖ 
That's the risk of ordering Kway chap as you will never know if the intestine for your order has been cleaned properly. 

Can't complain much as afterall, they specialised in duck rice.

~Haw Par Villa~

A day out visiting one of Singapore‚Äôs cultural heritage‚ù§Ô∏è

It‚Äôs been a long time since my last visit here but most things are pretty much still the same, which is a great thing (and some repainting works seemed to have taken place too)
Originally housed a huge villa that‚Äôs built by the Chinese-Burmese Aw Boon Haw for his beloved brother Aw Boon Par (hence the name Haw Par), that has since been destroyed after the World War II. Now it‚Äôs a public park housing statues & dioramas that serve to teach traditional Chinese values.
The one attraction that I remember the most is the Ten Courts of Hell which is a long trail of attraction depicting the judgement after life. It‚Äôs been turned into Hell‚Äôs museum recently that now requires $18 admission for adults, which‚Ä¶ I personally think is a bummer. 

Overall, it feels really nostalgic returning to this place since I grew up listening to these Chinese folklore stories. And to reread the history of the Haw Par brothers brings a new perspective to this park ‚ù§Ô∏è

Just the $18 admission to the Hell‚Äôs museum that‚Äôs a little disappointing. They may have introduced or revamped the place, I don‚Äôt know since we find it too costly to revisit the place that we‚Äôve been to before. And considering that the past history of this park that failed due to the costly admission park at that time just feels very dejavu in my opinion.

In any case, other parts of the park is still free for you to explore. So if you haven‚Äôt been here before (or in a long time) do come & visit! Just be ready with your mosquito repellantüòâ

Happy Friday!

[HOMECAFE Recipe] How about another refreshing and instagrammable drink for today? Citreon tea is a popular drink in Korea that is sweet and slightly sour. It is used as a herbal remedy to fight colds in Korea as the drink is filled with Vitamin C.

I am using store bought Honey Citreon marmalade (key ingredient in Citreon tea) and Bluepea flowers to make a delicious iced tea today. Here is how I did it -

Ingredients

-Dried Bluepea flowers 2 tbsp
-Hot Water 300ml
(Makes 2 Cups of Bluepea Tea)

-2 tbsp of Honey Yuzu/Citreon marmalade (available at Korean Supermarket or Specialty Stores)

-Ice (moderate amount)
-Room temperature water 50ml
-Lemon juice 1/2 TSP

1) Make Bluepea Tea. Pour boiling / hot water into dried Bluepea flowers. Set aside and let the tea cool down.

2) Add 2 tbsp Honey Yuzu into a glass. Add moderate amount of ice, followed by 50ml of water.

3) Add lemon juice into the glass.

4) Slowly pour the Bluepea Tea into the glass.

5) Garnish with a slice of lemon.

The drink is done!

[Review] Genuine Shanghai Zhu Chang fen Generously Filled With Ingredients At Just $3.80 For 2 rolls!

These Shanghai versions are found at Amoy Food Centre and the 3 flavours they offer are -

1. Mushroom, Minced Pork and Shrimp 
2. Chicken
3. Char Siew

We ordered a roll of Mushroom and a roll of Char Siew and here is our review of the 2 flavours.

Mushroom, Minced Pork and Shrimp
At first glance, we can see that the owner is generous with their sweet sauce and chilli üëç. The umami taste of shrimp and mushroom is prominent with each mouthful we took. There is a good bite to the minced pork, which is different from the more tender versions typical in slow cooked braised pork. We did enjoy this version, especially when paired with their flavourful chilli which we believe is made with dried shrimps as well!

Char siew
While the Hong Kong Style Char Siew in Chee Cheong Fun is usually moist and tender, their version is tougher, more chunky, and feels like eating Bak Kwa in our opinion. When eaten with their thin handmade Chee Chong Fun wrap, we get a blend of soft and hard textures with each bite. So if you like eating thicker cuts of Bak Kwa, you will like this version of Char Siew Chee Chong Fun.

We went to this stall at #01-03 on a quiet weekday morning. Based on our observations while we were there, this is the only stall on the ground floor of Amoy Food Centre with a regular flow of customers. We also saw a number of patrons ordering their chicken flavour. Overall we love the generous amount of ingredients and their well-made silky rice rolls, and will definitely return to try their chicken flavour ($3.80 for 2 rolls) and their yam cake which sells at $2.60 for 2 pieces. üòÄ

Genuine Shanghai Zhu Chang Fen
#01-03
Amoy Street Food Centre
7 Maxwell Rd, Singapore 069111

[Recipe] Tender and savoury Chicken And Vegetable Patties, that come with a bit of crunch from the use of vegetables! Taste really good with mayonnaise or sweet chilli too. Here is my simple recipe -

Ingredients

-Minced chicken meat, 375g
-Finely Chopped Mixed Vegetables, 250g (made up from 1 small carrot, half a medium size yellow onion, a few slices of cabbages and 40g of white beech mushrooms)
-3 large eggs
-2 cloves of garlic (finely grated)
-10g of ginger (finely grated)
-10g Salt
-15g Sugar
-Pepper (moderate)
-70g cake flour
-15g potato starch

1) Combine minced chicken meat and finely chopped mixed vegetables together. You can also explore using other vegetables that you prefer.

2) Mix part 1 with 3 large eggs, garlic, ginger, salt, sugar and a few dashes of pepper until well-combined.

3) Add 70g cake flour and 15g potato starch to the mixture in part 2 and mix well again.

4) Heat up some oil in a pan using medium heat and when the oil is hot, use an ice cream scoop or spoon to add batter to pan. Pan fry till one side is golden brown before flipping to other side.

The dish is done!

Fuel Plus+ is a popular cafe along a quiet street at Telok Blangah, and well known for their Brunch. And as their name suggests, if you need to "fuel up" for the day, @fuelplussg is the place to go.

Fuel Me Up + ($19)
This hearty dish is full of ingredients!! It comes with baked eggs with tomato sauce, chorizo style pork meatballs, sauteed peppers, sauteed mushrooms, chickpeas, Swiss cheese, peta cheese, potatoes, and topped with a crusty toast! This dish is big on flavours, yet not too tangy and very savoury. It can be cloying because it is very rich with all the cheeses, so we recommend to share.

Pulled Pork Rosti + ($17)
The "+" at the back tells you this is another energy boosting choice. I love the combination of russet and sweet potatoes used to make their rosti. The pulled pork was juicy and tender, and complements well when eaten with the crispy rocket salad and rosti. I feel the sunny side up fried egg is the "plus" of the dish, giving this dish that enticing look that makes one want to dig in immediately!

You can visit this cosy cafe at wishart road which is in the middle of a landed house cluster. There is a small alfresco area for those who love the outdoors. For those lucky enough, you may see the friendly neighbourhood rooster roaming around the area. üêìüòÄ

[Review] Our Love For Rainbow Food Continues....This time with a Rainbow Crepe Cake ($45 excluding delivery) from @happydoppi! We purchased this cake for our youngest daughter's birthday celebration as we thought it looks very cute and pretty.

Our previous experiences with crepe cakes were from well-known brands such as Chateraise and Lady M. In comparison to the crepe cake from these brands, the texture of this Rainbow cake is a lot more dimensional. We can taste the different layers distinctively, as well as the random slices of strawberries in between some of the layers. So while the cake is very soft and creamy, there is a chewiness / bite to this cake which is absent in the other brands we have tried.

Overall, a very interesting texture and we feel whether you will be a fan of this cake will largely depend on individual preference. If you prefer crepe cake layers that blend completely with the cream for a smooth finish, then this cake may not be for you.

What we really like about this cake from Happy Doppi is that it is not too sweet. It also comes with really thoughtful accessories such as a very meaningful gift tag with my daughter's name on it
(Swipe to see last picture), nice cake topper, pretty candles, four cute plates and forks.

If you like what we shared, go check out the offerings from @happydoppi!

It was leftovers for lunch yesterday‚Ä¶ veggie @quorn_uk chilli! I actually love a veggie chilli and make a few versions but this one is my fave full of flavour and warmth .. even my meat eaters love it!! 

üíú250g frozen quorn mince
üíú1 tbsp of olive oil and a knob of butter
üíú 1 red onion diced
üíú3 garlic cloves crushed
üíú1large carrot grated
üíú1 stick celery finely chopped
üíú 1 son chopped chilli
üíú1heaped tbsp tomato paste
üíú1tsp onion powder
üíú2tbsp cumin powder
üíú1 1/2 tbsp smoked paprika
üíú1tsp oregano
üíú1tsp black pepper
üíú1 tsp chilli powder
üíú1tin chopped tomatoes
üíú1/2tin kidney beans
üíú300ml veggie stock
üíú1tsp red wine vinegar
üíúSmall handful of chopped coriander plus some for garnish
üíúsqueeze of lime juice

üíú if you have any‚Ä¶ 1 tbsp maggi liquid seasoning‚Ä¶ it really elevates the flavour

Firstly gently fry the onions in the oil and butter for about 5 mins‚Ä¶ keep the heat low, then add the garlic, carrot , chilli and celery and continue to cook for another 2 to 3 mins.. add quorn, then it really is as simple as add all the other ingredients, bring to the boil and then reduce down to a simmer! I like to leave it cooking for about an hour as I think it gives a better flavour but it is ready quicker if you‚Äôre in a rush! Add a little water if it starts to dry out! When it‚Äôs done I like to gently mash it so all the veg and quorn come together better.. this dosent affect the quorn!!. And serve , salt to taste and garnish with a little coriander

Creamy sundried tomato chicken served with @cheshirefarm quality seasoned wedges and tenderstem broccoli!!

This one pan chicken dish is a real crowd pleaser and pretty quick on the table! Perfect for a weekday dinner! I served it with some of the wedges I was #gifted from @cheshirefarm and they went great together‚Ä¶ all that crispy potato goodness to mop up the sauce!! What‚Äôs even better about these award winning tatties is that they‚Äôre addidive  free and do taste like real potatoes and not the usual store bought ones that I always think taste weird!!!

üíú 400g chicken breast(thighs work good too!)
üíú1tsp olive oil and a knob of butter
üíú1 onion diced
üíú1 tbsp garlic paste
üíú1 heaped tablespoon sundried tomato paste
üíú50g of sundried tomatoes
üíú1tsp paprika
üíú1/2 tsp ground black pepper
üíú1tsp mixed herbs
üíú600ml good quality chicken stock
üíú80ml cream
üíúhandful of fresh herbs.. I used basil and parsley‚Ä¶ reserve some for garnish

Gently fry the onion in the olive oil and butter for about 5 mins, add the garlic paste and continue for 1-2 mins then add your chicken gently browning the outside. On a low heat add the tomato paste, sundried tomatoes, paprika, pepper and mixed herbs and mix well! Pour in the chicken stock and bring up to the boil before reducing down to a slow simmer! Allow to cook for around 20mins! Stir in the cream and let cook for another few mins then garnish with the leftover herbs and serve. Salt and pepper to taste

Mussels with spaghetti and a sundried tomato sauce with a good kick of chilli!!üå∂üå∂

I got some mussels from the fish market @fishplaiceglasgow yesterday! . I couldn‚Äôt wait to try them.. I feel like I haven‚Äôt had them in ages!! The sauce I made with tomatoes,  garlic,  onion, chillis, sundried tomatoes and a good glug of white wine !! They were just perfect !!

Did you know mussels, shellfish in general,are a great source of vitamin B12‚Ä¶ a vitamin that plays a big part in energy levels and one I‚Äôm deficient in as a side affect of my Crohn‚Äôs disease.  I do get injections for it but I like to back them up with as much shellfish as I can! ‚Ä¶.any excuse reallyüòÇü•∞ü•∞

üíúMussels, rinsed, scrubbed and debearded‚Ä¶ I used about 300g for two
Tbsp olive oil and a knob of butter
üíú1 onion dice
üíú3 garlic cloves crushed and finely chopped
üíú60g sundried tomatoes
üíú1tbsp sundried tomato paste 
üíú1-2 chillis dependence on your heat level
üíúSal pinch of sugar
üíú tin of tomatoes
üíú100ml veg stock
üíú120ml white wine I used Pinot Grigio
üíú fresh herbs.. I used basil and parsley
üíúpasta of choice

Gently fry onion and garlic In oil and butter for a few minutes, add the sundried tomato, tomato paste and chillis,cook for another minute.. then the tomatoes, stock,white wine,sugar and herbs leaving a little for garnish!.. bring to the boil then reduce down to a simmer! After about 15 minutes put the pasta on to cook and add the prepared mussels to the sauce, cover andcook.. check after about 5 mins.I like to remove the ones that are ready and open into a side bowl, cover for another two to three mins‚Ä¶ they should all be ready by now! Remove from pot! By this time the pasta should be almost cooked‚Ä¶ I transfer the pasta to the sauce and let it do the final bit of cooking in the sauce adding a little pasta water if necessary to loosen it up! Serve and add mussels, garnish, salt and pepper to taste

Frozen Margarita!

Sunday calls for one last chill before we fight our Monday blues again üò¨üòÆ‚Äçüí®

Chimichanga is a cute and vibrant place easily spotted in the corner of Holland V. Was supposed to eat here for dinner but it was full. Went back for drinks and luckily had a seat! (Or is it really lucky? üòÖ)

I had frozen margarita ($16+), while the rest ordered mojito ($18+) and chivas on the rocks ($14+). The margarita was poorly done. The salt was all over the rim (and lots of it) + even inside the drink :( really disappointed. Was expecting a better presentation too, but oh well ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è Ordered churros on the side ($10+ for 4pcs, not in photo) and again, it is brimming with salt. Had to tap it a few times and really dip into the choco to counter the taste

Not sure if it was just an unlucky night? We can opt to retry, but will def just order the nachos - which look very good btw (from neighbouring seats)

Ramen!

Yes, I know Ichiran is readily available in Donki, but eating the real one prepared in the restaurant is still way better (though overrated) ü•≤ Three photos here from the few times I‚Äôve tried it

First photo was from my 2020 Tokyo trip. Had this in the middle of a very hot afternoon. Ramen doesn‚Äôt choose any weather - good anytime, anywhere 

Second was from my 2019 Osaka trip wherein we tried it with beef broth. Surprisingly more subtle flavor. But pork > beef all the way üòÇ

And last was from 2018 trip to Taiwan. This is the most memorable one for me as we queued for almost 2h (first timers) outside, under the very cold weather + few hours remaining before our flight back home lol (so much for the hype). We were already very hungry and cold and really needed that ramen once we got in, that we enjoyed it a lot üòÇ you can see how hungry I was cause the photo is not focused at all lolol

Anyone here with memorable Ichiran ramen stories too? ü§ì let‚Äôs all reminisce till we can fly out and travel again üòÇ

Burger!

This big-ass Double Botak burger ($21.40 for the set) is super filling. The patties though huge, are very tender and juicy. The seasoning on the patties are flavourful which is elevated too by the grill taste.  Really enjoyable. It has the usual fillers of cheese, lettuce and tomatoes.

The set comes with spicy fries (can opt for non-spicy too) and coleslaw. There are other side options that can be chosen too.

Price is quite steep for a hawker stall though, and is almost at par with some mall burger chains. But basing on the serving size of both the main and the sides, I think it‚Äôs quite ok. (Still ex!! Lol) Might just order a la carte next time though as it‚Äôs very heavy for me üòÖ

Tom yum!

This Tom Yum Goong Soup ($10.15+), served with rice, had a generous amount of huge prawns - very fresh and cooked nicely (not tough at all). Soup is sour and quite spicy, but just enough to my liking.

Finding this place was a happy accident while I was looking for Pizza Hut to tapao my lunch from üòÇ place is quiet (idk on weekdays though as there are offices nearby), price is reasonable üëçüèª

Lobster and Chili Crab!

ü¶ûAustralian Lobster and Glass VermicellI Braised with "Sha Cha' Sauce in Claypot ($24.80++/100g). There‚Äôs an ongoing 50% off promo for this AU lobster so we opted for this instead of the Boston one ($13.80++/100g). We weren‚Äôt supposed to order this but the nearby table had it and it smelled so goooood. It didn‚Äôt disappont at all! This is the best dish for me. Sauce is very savoury and sweet. Lobster, though teeny-bit overcooked for me, is really good as well. 800g was just enough for the 5 of us. The vermicelli felt like bottomless, there‚Äôs just too much üòÇ

wow my friends can attest that i‚Äôm completely not a donut person but i easily devoured one on my own üòå ranks at the top of my list for donuts now!!!! #truffavs think soft, fluffy and chewy donuts lightly dusted with sugar granules and generously stuffed with smooth custard cream üëåüèªü§ç custard cream is v light and mildly sweet so it doesn‚Äôt get cloying even with how generous they are with it! if i were to nitpick, i‚Äôd prefer less sugar on the exterior though since the fillings are sweet enough

here‚Äôs the 3 flavours i tried, in order of preference!
ùêØùêöùêßùê¢ùê•ùê•ùêö ùêõùêûùêöùêß: this was rly good!!! not overly sweet like how vanilla tends to be and the cream was v light and fragrant. you can see the specks of the vanilla beans so that‚Äôs how you know you‚Äôre getting the real deal!!!

ùê°ùê®ùê£ùê¢ùêúùê°ùêö: the cream had a thicker consistency for this but nothing overwhelming! and i could taste rather distinct roasty and bittersweet notes of the hojicha ü•∞ as a hojicha fan, i‚Äôd love for it to be stronger but this would satisfy most people!

ùê≠ùêöùê´ùê® ùêúùê®ùêúùê®ùêßùêÆùê≠: the mildest out of the three, i couldn‚Äôt taste much coconut which i personally don‚Äôt mind! really appreciated how natural tasting the cream was but i expected a stronger taro flavour. could be slightly sweeter to let the flavour shine through!

niku king truly lives up to its name, just look at the generous amount of chashu!!! you won‚Äôt be needing to ration those slicesüëåüèº

i got the ùêßùê¢ùê§ùêÆ ùê§ùê¢ùêßùê† ùê≠ùê®ùêßùê§ùê®ùê≠ùê¨ùêÆ ùê´ùêöùê¶ùêûùêß ($ùüèùüë.ùüóùüé++) and compared to tonkotsu king, niku king‚Äôs broth is definitely richer and almost gelatinous since they use fattier meat. tbh it was so flavourful that i barely drank it üòÖ as for the chashu, they were really tender but slightly too fatty for my liking. i‚Äôm not a big fan of fatty meat so the best part for me was the noodles - thicker than usual ramen noodles and SO SPRINGY ü§©üíØ

didn‚Äôt get to try my friend‚Äôs ùêßùê¢ùê§ùêÆ ùê§ùê¢ùêßùê† ùê¨ùê°ùê®ùê≤ùêÆ ùê´ùêöùê¶ùêûùêß ($ùüèùüè.ùüóùüé++) though he commented on how salty the broth was. it‚Äôs soy sauce -based so i guess it‚Äôs to be expected!

üìçXiao Di Hokkien Mee

For our 100th post, we decided to introduce this amazing hokkien mee that is 100/100 in our books.

Located at Serangoon North Avenue 4, Xiao Di Hokkien Mee really whips up one of the most delicious plate of noodles we have ever eaten.

The noodles are served with prawns, pork slices and lard and gravy which is generously lathered on top. 

When we had our first bite, we immediately knew why there was so much hype about the store.

The noodles were cooked perfectly, and the prawn stock was just downright delicious. Loaded with plenty of prawn flavor, but yet not overpowering, the gravy went excellently with the yellow noodles. 

The prawns was big, juicy, and fresh and we devoured it in an instant. The pork slices were tender and added more flavors and texture to the dish as a whole and of course, the lard provides that extra crunch and saltiness that complements the noodles. 

Xiao Di is truly the best hokkien mee that we have had in Singapore, and we have had many amazing ones before. 

If you happen to be in the area, we will definitely recommend you pop by and grab yourself a plate.

Do note to check their opening hours before heading down though!

p.s. If xiao di can cook like this, we really wonder how amazing da ge‚Äôs noodles will beüåö

üìçMonday Blues

The only good Monday Blues is this dessert establishment, tucked along the outskirts of Geylang.

With a massive selection of 16 ice cream flavors to choose from (including interesting flavors like yuzu lemon, coconut, strawberry cheesecake etc) you‚Äôd be spoilt for choice committing to a flavor. Thankfully for us,  the ice cream here was affordably priced, making it a tad easier for us to get more scoops and to try more flavors.

 We opted for a double scoop salted caramel and speculoos ice cream with the waffles ($14) and was taken away by how well each flavor complemented with the fluffy and crisp waffles.

The Speculoos was downright decadence. The ice cream makers had to have been generous with the amount of speculoos used as the ice cream boasted a really strong and wholesome sweet biscuity flavor that paired nicely with the waffles. 

The salted caramel had just the right amount of saltiness and ate well with the waffles as well. Our only gripe was that there was a slight bitterness that came with it, but it was still pretty good overall. 

Of course, if you really had a sweet tooth or would like to try something fresh, you could opt for their cloudy ice cream waffles which comes with a ring of cotton candy surrounding the ice cream!

Our rating: 4/5

P.s. We know it‚Äôs a Monday but pretty sure you won‚Äôt have the blues if you drop by this sweet spot to chill after worküåö

üìçNY Verden

We used to only think about the beautiful fountain and the decadent ice cream in the form of a Birds of Paradise cone whenever we thought about Jewel. 

After trying out NY Verden, we now constantly muse about the artistically designed bar and grill whenever we speak about the attraction at Changi as well. 

We ordered the prosciutto as our appetizer and had the pork jowl and the guanciale with the gnocchi for our mains (yes, a lot of pork we know) and we are happy to say that every single dish was a hit with us. 

The prosciutto was flavorful, and the sweetness and the saltiness of the cured-ham really whetted our appetites and had us excited for the main dishes, just like a good appetizer should. 

We were mind blown when we tasted the pork jowl next. The meat was extremely tender, and completely melted in our mouths. It truly felt like we were having a Japanese wagyu version of pork because of how amazingly soft the meat was. To add icing on the cake, the meat was also fairly well seasoned.

The gnocchi was similarly well executed and unlike how most gnocchi that were soft and tender, NY Verden‚Äôs gnocchi was delicate, and had a very slight crisp at the exterior which added an interesting texture to the bite. Paired with the strong flavors from the guanciale, the dish was truly addictive and very enjoyable.

We thoroughly enjoyed ourselves at NY Verden, and we believe that you would too, so do give it a try if you happen to be popping by Jewel!

P.s. Helming the title of Top 15 SG masterchef and with old street BKT under its belt of culinary creations, it‚Äôs unsurprising that the latest addition, NY Verden, isn‚Äôt a burden to the gastronomy world.üåö

Our rating: 4.5/5

üìçKulto

From the outside, Kulto looks unassuming; just a simple restaurant with a neat layout, typical of many others.

The food that Kulto serves however, truly makes the restaurant stand out amongst the rest.

We ordered the set lunch, and decided to have the salmon tartare, the chicken and the cheesecake.

The tartare was exquisitely prepared, with the strong taste of the salmon balanced perfectly with the rich and creamy avocado. Combined with the added texture from the Ajo Blanco, the dish was a delight to the palate and a great way to start the meal.

We normally get the paella at Spanish establishments, but we decided on the chicken after hearing great reviews on it and were we ever glad we made the right choice. The chicken was tender and seasoned extremely well, and boasted a strong full flavor with every mouth taken. We were addicted to the subtle notes of fresh spices emanating from the meat and we finished the dish in a heart beat.

Of course, no meal is ever complete without a dessert and are we glad to say that Kulto ensured that we finished off the meal with a bang. The burnt basque cheesecake was oozing out delicious molten cheese that paired really well with the raspberry sorbet. Some cheesecakes are too sweet or too cheesy, but Kulto's one hit the spot just right.

Getting such a great set lunch at the CBD area for $40 is truly a steal in our opinion and we will definitely be back at Kulto for more delicious culinary treats.

p.s. if there ever was a Kulto Kult we will be the first to enroll in it.

üìçKoma

At Koma, you don‚Äôt have to wait for safe travel lanes to be established with Japan before you can immerse yourself completely in üáØüáµ‚Äôs culture! (you might have to wait for a month or two due to the wait list though)

As you walk into Koma, you are instantly reminded of quaint Kyoto, with the decor of it's entrance similar to that of the famous Fushimi Inari shrine. The interior of the restaurant was spacious and it's design was absolutely beautiful. 

What was more beautiful though was the food itself. The dishes were well-executed and delightfully plated and was truly a work of art.

The unassuming salmon pillows was a delightful surprise to our taste buds. The texture of the crispy pastry puff complemented well with the thick tender slice of salmon sashimi and there was an explosion of flavor when we bit into the smoked avocado and burnt jalepeno filling.

The beef and foie gras skewer was delicious as well, with the rich and creamy foie gras layering onto the juicy and tender beef cubes. 

All in all, Koma though pricey is definitely a place where you would want to try out.

Our rating : 4.5/5

p.s. They‚Äôre not lying when they names themselves koma, cause a food koma is almost guaranteed or you‚Äôd pray for a koma when you see the prices üôÉ

Blumenk√§se - or ‚Äúblossoms cheese" hits your eyes before it hits your tongue. Covered herbs and wildflowers from the meadows of Switzerland: winter savory, dill, garlic, caraway, lovage, marjoram, mint, leek, chive, parsley, juniper berries, onion, marigolds, cornflower, roses, strawberry leaves. This alpine cheese is one of my favourites.
. 
The taste: A delicate umami acidity, slightly earthy hint of grass and straw. Someone described it as ‚Äòmountain savoury‚Äô - the perfect description!
.
If you scroll left, you‚Äôll see an example, in the village of Tschierschen, of the Swiss faith in compliance. A little village shop selling the area‚Äôs speciality cheese, sausage, honey. ‚ÄúCome on in, we‚Äôre open‚Äù, says the sign. You walk into a tiny room with two refrigerators, a ledger and a cash box. Nobody watching you. Take your produce, pay and record it in the ledger, go on your merry way. What a wonderful way to live!
.
